      <h1>"Follow me" - an experiment</h1>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    <i>
      The amount of money we spend on social-media marketing is 
      staggering. The yearly spend in the US alone is in the high billions.
      Greedily inspired by such a mega-spend, the goal of this experiment is to simply 
      make people follow an arbitrary account on twitter. 
      The design of the experiment is guided by BJ Fogg's behavior model, which
      states that behavior change (B) is a function of motivation (M), ability (A),
      and triggering (T).
    </i>
  </p>
  <hr>
  <div class="clearfix" >
    <div style="float:left;font-size:80px">
      <i class="icon-beaker"></i>
    </div>
    <div style="margin-left:20px;float:left">
      <h4>The experiment in terms of B, M, A and T</h4>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    <b>Behavior [B]</b> (cause someone to) follow a given twitter account.
  </p>
  <p>
    <b>Trigger [T]</b> The trigger is a canonical social network 'hot trigger'.
  </p>
  <p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Code scrapes twitter for tweets containing certain words. Filtering-by-words 
        is how we pinpoint our 'desired audience'.
      </li>
      <li>
        When an appropriate tweet is found, the code favorites that tweet, on behalf of
        the user using this code tool.
      </li>
      <li>
        Twitter sends an email / mobile notification to the user, saying that their tweet that was favorited.
        Also the notification will show up in the connect tab on twitter.com / mobile devices. The connect
        tab will now be highlighted since there's something new there.
      </li>
      <li>
        The notification contains the a bio of the favoriters account - and a big button prompting the
        recipient to follow that user.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    <b>Ability [A]</b> The users ability (or 'simplicity') to perform the desired behavior is extremely high.
    Most users will receive the notification via 3 channels.  
  </p>
  <p>
    <ol>
      <li>On twitter.com in the connect tab</li>
      <li>On their mobile device as a OS level notification and in the connect tab</li>
      <li>In their email inbox</li>
    </ol>
    In each case the desired behavior is <i>2 clicks away</i>. The first click takes you to 
    the users twitter profile, and the second click (on a big 'Follow' button) allows you to follow
    the user.
  </p>
  <p>
    <b>Motivation [M] - Social Cohesion & Anticipation</b>
  </p>
  <p>
    <i>Social Cohesion</i> is a motivator in this experiment as the recipient of the
    favorite wants to feel connected to this nice person who's appreciating their tweets.
    It's also possible that the recipient will fear social rejection if he/she doesn't
    show some sign of appreciation for the favorite.
  </p>
  <p>
    <i>Anticipation</i> is a motivator as the recipient anticipates future positive
    signals from this user (which make them feel good). Also, the recipient is anticipating
    future information consumption originating from this user. This might take the form of
    images, video, news articles, entertaining tweets etc.
  </p>
