  <p>
    The experiment was shockingly successful at achieving the desired behavior. All 3 participants
    more than doubled their daily follower gain rate.
  </p>
  <p>
    To put this in terms of BJ Fogg's behavior model, the experiment was successful 
    due to the following characteristics:
    <ol>
      <li>Motivation: this was definitely the smallest force. Certainly not comparable
      to the motivation to loose weight, quit smoking or have sex. However there's a 
      reasonable desire for social cohesion, as well as an anticipation of future favorites
      and information/entertainment.</li>
      <li>Triggers: Email notification, mobile OS notifications and connect tab notifications
      on twitter.com and twitter mobile apps. The trigger comes in the form of a positive
      social gesture from one user to another. The 'FOLLOW' button included in these triggers
      is prominent and looks deliciously clickable</li>
      <li>Ability: this was extremely high. Once the trigger is presented, 
      fulfilment of desired behavior is a mere
      2 clicks away - easy for anyone.</li>
    </ol>
  </p>

